>>12808828
Time skips are totally workable, the active time just needs to be nice and salient. Writing 100% in continuity gets overly dense on large scale given how much of life is down time. That's been a major downfall in a lot of my early fiction. Being a Skyfag/rocketfag/ /o/ fag has resulted in travel being a big theme in a lot of my projects, and I've spent no small amount of time researching how others deal with elapsing time in travel. Most of the time, the answer seems to be that they simply don't. My last serious project was a memoir about a childhood road trip; that one I approached by letting a brief sentence-or-two description of whatever book-on-tape I was listening to for that leg of the journey serve as an interlude. That project was received very well (still have my fingers crossed that one of the journals I submitted to will pick it up), so in my relatively limited experience, that sort of approach to the problem seems functional.

If there's a key to it, it seems to be avoiding falling into the passive voice for awhile in summarizing what happened while we weren't "watching". If we didn't need to see it first hand, we probably don't have to know much about it at all. Whatever you're doing seems to be working though, so I wouldn't agonize over it. I'd you need to elapse time, just do it.

I listen to Spotify's Calm Before the Storm playlist usually when I write, but lately I've been listening the Christmas Peaceful Piano playlist.

There is a list of reasons for this, but mostly you just don't want the extra words being thrown into your brain, and your mind is trying to find a rhythm.
